{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 380 "A
 related theorem about finding roots of polynomials (equivalently fact
oring polynomials into a product of linear factors) asserts that if th
e polynomial has real coefficients -- all of the polynomials we have c
onsidered (and will consider) have had real coefficients -- then any c
omplex roots (or factors) must occur in conjugate pairs.  For example,
 both the complex factors of " }{TEXT 288 5 "F, G " }{TEXT -1 4 "and \+
" }{TEXT 289 2 "H " }{TEXT -1 236 "(above) all occurred in conjugate p
airs.  Demonstrate this theorem by creating three new polynomials, nam
e them F1, G1 and H1, of degree 5, 6 and 7, resp., and show that the a
ny complex factors of F1, G1 and H1 occur in conjugate pairs." }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 
10 "(F1/H1)/G;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(%#F1G\"\"\"%#H1G!
\"\"%\"GGF'" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 
"" {MPLTEXT 1 0 11 "F1/(H1/G1);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(%
#F1G\"\"\"%#H1G!\"\"%#G1GF%" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 
9 "F1/H1*G1;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(%#F1G\"\"\"%#H1G!\"
\"%#G1GF%" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 64 "I do not understand what else you w
ant me to do in this section." }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 
0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 115 "For demonstration purposes it \+
is very handy to be able to construct polynomials with predetermined r
oots.  Use the " }{TEXT 258 6 "expand" }{TEXT -1 58 " command to const
ruct a polynomial with roots   -2, 5, 5, " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "-1/2" "6#,$
*&\"\"\"F%\"\"#!\"\"F'" }{TEXT -1 71 ", 1+I and  1-I.  (Here the \"5, \+
5\" indicates that 5 is a \"double root\".)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 307 2 "kp" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 45 "1.  Some of the functions
 are not initialized" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 45 "2.  Some of the f
unctions are not initialized" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "3.  " }}
{PARA 257 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 27 "Factor each polynomial and " }{TEXT 
308 9 "determine" }{TEXT -1 157 " whether Maple was able to find enoug
h linear factors to demonstrate the above assertion about the appropri
ate number of linear factors.    Did you do that??" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 70 "Why did f1 (which was a d
egree 7 polynomial) have sooooooo many roots?" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 79 "Did you construct example
s to show that roots occur in complex conjugate pairs?" }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 5 "4.5/6" }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 5 "2.5/4" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "6/10" }}{PARA 0 
"" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 309 5 "13/20" }}{PARA 0 
"" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 46 "4.  Binomial Theorem.  Use the Maple command  " }
{TEXT 290 6 "expand" }{TEXT 256 2 "  " }{TEXT -1 34 "to calculate the \+
expansion of     " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(a+b)^n;" "6#),&%\"aG\"\"\"%\"bGF&%
\"nG" }{TEXT -1 63 "    for values n=1..10 .  In each case use the Map
le command   " }{TEXT 257 7 "coeffs " }{TEXT 292 1 " " }{TEXT -1 84 "t
o pick off the coefficients.   For example,  if n=5 we would execute t
he following:" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 27 "expand((a+b
)^5);\ncoeffs(%);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,.*$)%\"aG\"\"&\"
\"\"F(*(F'F()F&\"\"%F(%\"bGF(F(*(\"#5F()F&\"\"$F()F,\"\"#F(F(*(F.F()F&
F2F()F,F0F(F(*(F'F(F&F()F,F+F(F(*$)F,F'F(F(" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6(\"#5\"\"&F#\"\"\"F%F$" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 28 "
Do the rest from 1 to 10.   " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 31 "Note:  it
 is possible to use a " }{TEXT 291 9 "for loop " }{TEXT -1 69 " to sim
plify this task since we are doing a repetitive calculation.  " }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 29 "Note:  Also, the the command " }{TEXT 
293 6 "coeffs" }{TEXT -1 15 " unfortunately " }{TEXT 294 8 "does not" 
}{TEXT -1 36 " pick off the coefficients in order." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "The " }{TEXT 260 16 "Binom
ial Theorem" }{TEXT -1 66 " gives a formula for finding the coefficien
ts of the expansion of " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(a+b)^n;" "6#),&%\"aG\"\"\"%
\"bGF&%\"nG" }{TEXT -1 10 "  for any " }{TEXT 295 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 53 "
.  It is relatively obvious that the coefficient of  " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 
"a^k*b^(n-k);" "6#*&)%\"aG%\"kG\"\"\")%\"bG,&%\"nGF'F&!\"\"F'" }{TEXT 
-1 19 "  for any value of " }{TEXT 296 1 "k" }{TEXT -1 11 " from 0 to \+
" }{TEXT 297 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 46 " is given by the number of ways we ca
n choose " }{TEXT 298 1 "k" }{TEXT -1 8 " of the " }{TEXT 300 1 "a" }
{TEXT -1 12 "'s from the " }{TEXT 299 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 1 " " }{TEXT 
301 1 "a" }{TEXT -1 20 "'s in the expansion " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(a+b)*(a
+b)" "6#*&,&%\"aG\"\"\"%\"bGF&F&,&F%F&F'F&F&" }{TEXT -1 7 " ....( " }
{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(a+b)" "6#,&%\"aG\"\"\"%\"bGF%" }{TEXT -1 4 " ), " }
{TEXT 302 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 41 " times .   The number of combinations of
 " }{TEXT 303 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 18 " objects choosing " }{TEXT 304 1 "k
" }{TEXT -1 12 " at a time, " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "nCk" "6#%$nCkG" }{TEXT 
-1 27 ", is given by the formula  " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "nCk=n!/(k!*(n-k)!)
" "6#/%$nCkG*&-%*factorialG6#%\"nG\"\"\"*&-F'6#%\"kGF*-F'6#,&F)F*F.!\"
\"F*F2" }{TEXT -1 2 " ." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT 262 10 "State the " }{TEXT 261 16 "Binomial Theorem" }
{TEXT -1 1 " " }{TEXT 305 31 "and use Maple to demonstrate it" }{TEXT 
-1 1 "." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 8 
"Compute " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "sum(binomial(n,k),k=0..n)" "6#-%$sumG6$-%)b
inomialG6$%\"nG%\"kG/F*;\"\"!F)" }{TEXT -1 34 "  for n=1 to 10.  Here \+
the symbol " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "Sigma;" "6#%&SigmaG" }{TEXT -1 70 " (Gree
k letter Sigma) stands for sum.   (See the worksheet SumSeq.mws)" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 259 59 "What gen
eral formula do the above calculations in  suggest?" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 388 "5.  Pascal's Triangle.
  Recall the definition of Pascal's Triangle.   Use Maple to construct
 the first 10 rows of Pascal's Triangle. (The trick will be to get the
 coefficients to occur in the correct order.  The Maple command for ge
nerating a sequence might be helpful. It is   seq(expression(i),i=m..n
);   where expression(i) is an expression with index i and m..n is a r
ange of numbers." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 4 "    " }}}{MARK "197 0" 0 }{VIEWOPTS 1 1 0 1 1 1803 1 1 1 1 }
